CentOS 8 has been released and most of the organizations looking forward to upgrade their existing installations of CentOS 7 based servers to CentOS 8. 
Here, we are performing a complete upgrade of CentOS 7 to CentOS 8

There are many alternate ways to upgrade your CentOS 7 based applications and databases to CentOS 8. Here, we are executing an in-place upgrade of existing CentOS 7 server 
with installed applications and databases to the lastest versions provided by CentOS 8 server.

Since you are upgrading your environment from CentOS 7 to CentOS 8, therefore, it is recommended that you should also upgrade yourself and technical resources as well.

Environment Specification:
We are using a virtual machine configured as CentOS 7 LAMP server.

CPU - 3.4 Ghz (2 cores)
Memory - 2 GB
Storage - 20 GB
Operating System - CentOS 7.7
Hostname - centos-7-server.sysadminlabs.com
IP Address - 192.168.116.215 /24
 

Gathering System Information of CentOS 7:
Connect with centos-7-server.sysadminlabs.com as root user by using an ssh tool like PuTTY.

Check the current version of Linux Kernel.

[root@centos-7-server ~]# uname -r
3.10.0-1062.7.1.el7.x86_64

Check the current version of Apache HTTP Server.

[root@centos-7-server ~]# httpd -v
Server version: Apache/2.4.6 (CentOS)
Server built:   Aug  8 2019 11:41:18

Check the current version of PHP.

[root@centos-7-server ~]# php -v
PHP 5.4.16 (cli) (built: Nov  1 2019 16:04:20)
Copyright (c) 1997-2013 The PHP Group
Zend Engine v2.4.0, Copyright (c) 1998-2013 Zend Technologies

Check the current version of MariaDB server.

[root@centos-7-server ~]# mysql -V
mysql  Ver 15.1 Distrib 5.5.64-MariaDB, for Linux (x86_64) using readline 5.1

Open URL http://centos-7-server.sysadminlabs.com in a browser.

01-upgrade-centos-7-to-8-phpinfo-5

 

Installing EPEL yum Repository on CentOS 7:
We are required some packages that are available in EPEL (Extra Packages for Enterprise Linux) yum repository.

Therefore, we are installing epel-release package to enable EPEL yum repository.

